


HOSTNAME(1)         Linux Programmer's Manual         HOSTNAME(1)


NNAAMMEE
       hostname - show or set the system's host name
       domainname - show or set the system's NIS/YP domain name
       dnsdomainname - show the system's DNS domain name
       nisdomainname - show or set system's NIS/YP domain name
       ypdomainname - show or set the system's NIS/YP domain name
       nodename - show or set the system's DECnet node name


SSYYNNOOPPSSIISS
       hhoossttnnaammee [--vv] [--aa] [----aalliiaass] [--dd] [----ddoommaaiinn] [--ff] [----ffqqddnn]
       [--ii]  [----iipp--aaddddrreessss]  [----lloonngg]  [--ss] [----sshhoorrtt] [--yy] [----yypp]
       [----nniiss] [--nn] [----nnooddee]


       hhoossttnnaammee [--vv] [--FF ffiilleennaammee] [----ffiillee ffiilleennaammee] [hhoossttnnaammee]


       ddoommaaiinnnnaammee [--vv] [--FF ffiilleennaammee] [----ffiillee ffiilleennaammee] [nnaammee]


       nnooddeennaammee [--vv] [--FF ffiilleennaammee] [----ffiillee ffiilleennaammee] [nnaammee]


       hhoossttnnaammee [--vv] [--hh] [----hheellpp] [--VV] [----vveerrssiioonn]


       ddnnssddoommaaiinnnnaammee [--vv]
       nniissddoommaaiinnnnaammee [--vv]
       yyppddoommaaiinnnnaammee [--vv]


DDEESSCCRRIIPPTTIIOONN
       HHoossttnnaammee is the program that is used to either set or dis­
       play  the current host, domain or node name of the system.
       These names are used by many of the networking programs to
       identify  the  machine.  The  domain  name is also used by
       NIS/YP.


   GGEETT NNAAMMEE
       When called without any arguments,  the  program  displays
       the current names:


       hhoossttnnaammee  will print the name of the system as returned by
       the ggeetthhoossttnnaammee(2) function.


       ddoommaaiinnnnaammee,, nniissddoommaaiinnnnaammee,,  yyppddoommaaiinnnnaammee  will  print  the
       name  of  the  system  as returned by the ggeettddoommaaiinnnnaammee(2)
       function. This is also known as the YP/NIS domain name  of
       the system.


       nnooddeennaammee  will print the DECnet node name of the system as
       returned by the ggeettnnooddeennaammee(2) function.


       ddnnssddoommaaiinnnnaammee will print  the  domain  part  of  the  FQDN
       (Fully  Qualified  Domain  Name). The complete FQDN of the
       system is returned with hhoossttnnaammee ----ffqqddnn.


   SSEETT NNAAMMEE
       When called with one argument or with the  ----ffiillee  option,
       the  commands set the host name, the NIS/YP domain name or
       the node name.


       Note, that only the super-user can change the names.


       It is not possible to set the FQDN or the DNS domain  name
       with the ddnnssddoommaaiinnnnaammee command (see TTHHEE FFQQDDNN below).


       The  host  name  is  usually set once at system startup in
       _/_e_t_c_/_r_c_._d_/_r_c_._i_n_e_t_1 or _/_e_t_c_/_i_n_i_t_._d_/_b_o_o_t (normally by  read­
       ing  the  contents of a file which contains the host name,
       e.g.  _/_e_t_c_/_h_o_s_t_n_a_m_e).


   TTHHEE FFQQDDNN
       You can't change the FQDN (as returned by hhoossttnnaammee ----ffqqddnn)
       or the DNS domain name (as returned by ddnnssddoommaaiinnnnaammee) with
       this command. The FQDN of the system is the name that  the
       rreessoollvveerr(3) returns for the host name.


       Technically: The FQDN is the name ggeetthhoossttbbyynnaammee(2) returns
       for the host name returned  by  ggeetthhoossttnnaammee(2).   The  DNS
       domain name is the part after the first dot.

       Therefore  it  depends  on  the  configuration (usually in
       _/_e_t_c_/_h_o_s_t_._c_o_n_f) how you can change  it.  Usually  (if  the
       hosts  file is parsed before DNS or NIS) you can change it
       in _/_e_t_c_/_h_o_s_t_s.



OOPPTTIIOONNSS
       _-_a_, _-_-_a_l_i_a_s
              Display the alias name of the host (if used).

       _-_d_, _-_-_d_o_m_a_i_n
              Display the name of the DNS domain. Don't  use  the
              command  ddoommaaiinnnnaammee  to  get  the  DNS  domain name
              because it will show the NIS domain  name  and  not
              the DNS domain name. Use ddnnssddoommaaiinnnnaammee instead.

       _-_F_, _-_-_f_i_l_e _f_i_l_e_n_a_m_e
              Read  the  host  name from the specified file. Com­
              ments (lines starting with a `#') are ignored.

       _-_f_, _-_-_f_q_d_n_, _-_-_l_o_n_g
              Display the FQDN (Fully Qualified Domain  Name).  A
              FQDN  consists  of  a  short  host name and the DNS
              domain name. Unless you are using bind or  NIS  for
              host  lookups  you  can change the FQDN and the DNS
              domain name (which is part  of  the  FQDN)  in  the
              _/_e_t_c_/_h_o_s_t_s file.

       _-_h_, _-_-_h_e_l_p
              Print a usage message and exit.

       _-_i_, _-_-_i_p_-_a_d_d_r_e_s_s
              Display the IP address(es) of the host.

       _-_n_, _-_-_n_o_d_e
              Display  the  DECnet  node  name. If a parameter is
              given (or ----ffiillee nnaammee ) the root can also set a new
              node name.

       _-_s_, _-_-_s_h_o_r_t
              Display  the short host name. This is the host name
              cut at the first dot.

       _-_V_, _-_-_v_e_r_s_i_o_n
              Print version information on  standard  output  and
              exit successfully.

       _-_v_, _-_-_v_e_r_b_o_s_e
              Be verbose and tell what's going on.

       _-_y_, _-_-_y_p_, _-_-_n_i_s
              Display  the  NIS  domain  name.  If a parameter is
              given (or ----ffiillee nnaammee ) then root can  also  set  a
              new NIS domain.

FFIILLEESS
       //eettcc//hhoossttss

